    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-03-27T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-03-27T03:00:00-05:00" n="286"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d286">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">840.6362/3–2747: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-03-27T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >March 27, 1947—11 a. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1046. <gloss target="#t_DelsecSecdel1">Delsec</gloss> 1354. For Acheson. Personal
                    from Marshall. Reference British request to <gloss target="#t_ECO1">ECO</gloss>
                    for allocation of coal from US in third quarter. Department’s 618, March 21
                        (<gloss target="#t_Secdel1">Secdel</gloss> 1362).</p>
                <pb facs="0515" n="497" xml:id="pg_497"/>
                <p>Department should take position that it is reluctant to allocate coal to British
                    as British availabilities from own production without exports are considerably
                    closer to normal availabilities than the quantities available to continental
                    countries.</p>
                <p>Transport difficulties make it unlikely that additional coal may be shipped in
                    third quarter and allocation to British could be made only by reduction in
                    allocation to continent. Allocations of US coal to British under these
                    circumstances, unless wholeheartedly supported by <gloss target="#t_ECO1"
                        >ECO</gloss> importing countries, would lead to misunderstanding and
                    bitterness.</p>
                <p>This reply will leave the door open if Bevin desires to appeal to me. I prefer
                    not to initiate discussion with him.</p>
                <p>Repeated to London as 108.</p>
                <closer>[<signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                    </signed>]</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
